content.description: Climb the rippled slab that faces directly downhill.  Start with hands on opposing aretes, hike feet over the lip and balance your way up to the lip.  A fun and committing problem!
content.protection: A few pads to fill holes in the talus
content.location: Downhill face of the Ocean Floor Boulder

content.description: This is the low start to Dolphin Fingers and the whole line in my opinion. Start with your right hand on the arete, left on a toothy and small 3 finger hold just above the lip. Climb leftwards along the lip. This is a physical compression problem and the moves are super fun.
content.protection: A few pads and A SPOTTER.. seriously have a spotter, you can fall off the ramp and possibly have a very bad fall. It has happened more than once. With a spotter though life is good.

content.description: Sit Start on the bottom corner of the boulder with good in-cut crimps.  Perch the feet high and avoid the dab as you move up the left hand arete and holds out right.  Top out directly above.
content.location: Front Corner of Ocean Floor Boulder

content.description: Mantle the overhanging block on the right side of the Ocean Floor Boulder.  Begin standing at the jugs in the break and surmount the quartzite bulge above you.
content.location: Right side of the Ocean Floor Boulder

content.description: Start with a left hand sidepull and right hand on three-finger dish above the lip.  Pull on with heel hooks and tension, move across the slopey lip eventually culminating in a toss for the lip jug.
content.location: Ocean Floor Boulder - Located between Ice Queen & the Fukness.  Boulder sits 100 feet up in the talus and faces directly down hill.  It's a triangle shaped boulder with beautiful ripples laden in the rock.

content.description: A triangular boulder with a rippled slab of a face.
